{"cursor":"32696","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":", showing the 'Legio III Augusta', stationed at Lambaesis (Batna, Algeria), in\nMauretania Caesariensis province, from CE 75 until the 4th century]]\n\n'Legio tertiaAugusta' ('ThirdAugustanLegion') was a Roman legion raised in the\nyear 43 BCE most likely by the consul Gaius Vibius Pansa and the emperor\nAugustus who served the Roman Empire in North Africa until at least the late 4th\ncentury CE. It is possible that it fought in the battle of Philippi against the\nmurderers of Caesar. It is probable that the Legion served Augustus while he\nwaged war against Sextus Pompeius who threatened the grain supply from Africa to\nRome. After he had won, Augustus turned on Lepidus and defeated him, winning the\nprovince of Africa in the process. The next movement of the legion is unclear\nbut âit is certain that from 30 BCE on, the Third was permanently in Africa,\nalthough it was not always stationed in the same camp.\" Livius: Articles on Ancient History. http://www.livius.org/ta-\ntd/tacfarinas/tacfarinas.html The increasing importance of the grain\nsupply from Africa made the presence of the legion all the more important. Yann Le Bohec, The Imperial Roman Army (New York:\nHippocrene, 1994), Print. The legion suffered several wars, constant\nborder skirmishes, rebellions, disbandment, reformation, and yet, it managed to\ndefend Northern Africa for a period of 500 years. During this time, it was a\nmilitary force but more so, it was a building and cultural force that was a\nmajor mover in the urbanization of the province.\n","linknr":358,"url":"Legio_III_Augusta","recorded":1374520045,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Legio_III_Augusta&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Legio_III_Augusta&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bi